			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>Towards Dynamic Evolution of Domain Specific Languages</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/PaulRLaird.html">Paul R. Laird</a>, <a href="../profile/StephenBarrett.html">Stephen Barrett</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_11">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_11</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagM">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> The contribution is about evolving DSLs dynamically, i.e., handling change and maintenance of language definitions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The subject of evolution is domain-specific languages.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> Dynamic evolution often relies on tooling support for deploying/adjusting DSL implementations.
</li></ul></li></ul>
